						<p class="mt-4 text-[1.2rem] sm:ml-8">
							Did improved housing conditions contribute to the 19th century mortality transition?
							In this paper we examine a rare example of a public health intervention in rural
							areas, namely the large-scale provision of social housing in Ireland in the late 19th
							and early 20th centuries. We exploit a novel dataset of deaths-by-disease,
							deaths-by-age and the implementation of the house building scheme across local
							districts over the period 1870-1919, to test the impact of the intervention on
							mortality. Both two-way fixed-effects and novel difference-in-difference estimators
							show that areas that received more cottages experienced a larger decline in disease
							mortality over subsequent decades. Our estimates indicate that improved housing
							conditions may account for up to 40 % of the rural mortality decline in this period.
							This effect is driven by reductions in deaths from respiratory diseases. A causal
							interpretation is supported by falsification tests on deaths from non-communicable
							diseases and through an analysis using age-at-death and death-by-gender data. Beyond
							indicating that large-scale capital public health interventions can be effective in a
							rural setting, our results add to the literature of the European mortality transition
							and provide important causal evidence on the link between housing conditions and
							health outcomes.
						</p>
